node.text:
Three weeks of hard labor, raw emotions, endless trial and error, sweat, anger, frustration, and many, many tears are finally put to rest as we arrive at our studio and click Publish.

Will our fans like the illustration? Will they connect with the emotion? 

All of a sudden, the comments start pouring in, and we are reminded, once again, of why we do what we do. 

This is us, fully exposed and vulnerable as we take in the sudden tidal wave of heartfelt congratulations and love from our followers all over the world. 

This is our labor of love. 

For you. ❤️

Dedicated to our amazing fans around the world!

We wanna thank the amazing team that worked with us on this series! Thanks to you it came out so perfect!!!

- @theuddu
- @gal.hamo
- @yossun10
- @matan_balalty
- @tamiravidor
- @skyvideo_aerials
- @segev_idan

Thank you!!!!!

node.text:
As the old saying goes, you can't make an omelette without breaking a few eggs.  When you're the chef, working on your creation, it's no big deal. You do what you have to do to and move on. But once in awhile, the work turns on us, and WE are the eggs. WE are the problem and the only way to solve it -  no matter how painful - is to take each other by the hand and face it head on. So what do you do when the artwork is all wrong? You put your egos aside, trust in your partner's love, and break the damn eggs.

Being married to your work partner is a blessing on most days, but when two creative, opinionated (and oh-so tired) artists can’t agree on an illustration that is so important to us, egos clash, frustration builds up, and the tension rarely stays in the studio.

Here’s a personal, candid glimpse into our creative process and how every other aspect of our lives impacts our art. How do you tell your husband, just 3 short days before the big publication date, that we need to toss out the existing artwork and start from scratch? 

Will we overcome the creative obstacle at the last minute or will we succumb to pressure?

In October, 2020, we finally announced Maya’s second pregnancy to the world. Unlike most illustrations, however, the creation process for this particular comic took a serious toll on us, both creatively and emotionally. After endless brainstorming sessions and dozens of sketches, we finally realized why we weren’t getting it: We wouldn’t nail the visual until we figured out the emotion we wanted to convey with this piece. Our journey wasn’t physical, but rather an emotional one.

Sitting down to brainstorm about what exactly we would want the artwork to convey in this special comic, Yehuda recalls how he felt after Ariel (our first child) was born. We didn’t know it then, but he went through a dark, lengthy battle with postpartum depression. Not a man of many words, he dealt with it the way he deals with most of his emotions - through his art. ❤️

node.text:
📢 Online Course - The Art of One Frame 📢

▪️WHO IS THIS CLASS FOR? 

This class is for anyone who wants to learn the basics of digital drawing to how to create and maintain a community on social media. Especially if you want to make a living out of your hobby and get the recognition creators desire the most! 

▪️WHAT WILL THE STUDENTS ACHIEVE? 

When you’ve completed the course, you will have a better understanding of full digital illustration along with how to expose your art on social media and get the most out of it. We will take you hand in hand and teach you how to build a successful brand from your art just like we did it! All the secrets! All the knowledge and experience we have acquired over the years of creating online. 

▪️WHAT YOU WILL LEARN?

➡️ Step 1: The art of facial expression: how to speak with now words. 

➡️ Step 2: Master the Anatomy of the human body and muscle structure.

➡️ Step 3: Sketch, ink, coloring, and everything in between for creating a masterpiece. 

➡️ Step 4: Learning the art of storytelling in one frame. 

➡️ Step 5: How to make money from your art? 

❤ SEE YOU THERE!!! ❤

#judedevir #mayadevir #oneofthosedays #class101
